title_full:
Mixmaster Morris, Jonah Sharp, Haruomi Hosono

              —
              Quiet Logic
            
              (WRWTFWW Records)
label: WRWTFWW Records
description:
Allow Mixmaster Morris, YMO’s Haruomi Hosono, and US electronica pioneer Jonah Sharp to nuzzle nostalgia nozzles on a first vinyl pressing of their 1997 ambient dance saga - a big RIYL The Irresistible Force, Spacetime Continuum, Dreamfish, Tetsu Inoue, FFWD, H.I.A., Fax +49-69/450464

Mana for backroom psychonauts and yoghurt weavers, ‘Quiet Logic’ pitches a trio of electronic music dreamers in fluid, harmonious fusion for just under an hour of gently trippy ambient soundscaping. Mostly... more

label: Astrophonica
description:
Sully meets Manchester vocalist Sâlo on a taut, soulful pearl backed with an expansive dub fizzing with signature details

’Nights’ pitches Sully in previously unexplored terrain, injecting a dose of contemporary soul via Sâlo’s vocal to tight, tungsten-tipped breaks programming and late Dillinja-style distorted bass to a near-dance-pop-soul brief. His ‘Nights (Not Just a Dub Mix)’ is perhaps more recognisably Sully, opening out the vocal and drums in acres of warehouse space with reeling... more

title_full:
Various Artists

              —
              Alley of the Sun
            
              (Not Not Fun)
label: Not Not Fun
description:
Raise a glass to 20 years of Not Not Fun with their 400th (!!!) release, a sublime cross-section of sidelong psych, lower case club music and new new age ambient by a constellation of alumni and affiliates who all chime with the sound.

For two decades NNF has been a reliable source of lysergic sauce from the peripheries and blind spots of the 3rd eye, weathering multiple vibe shifts and playing instrumental roles in movements such as vaporware, lo-fi house (both on main and sister label... more

label: Refreshers
description:
Lukid returns on a soulfully rinsed-out old skool jungle lash under his Refreshers alias, including a tremendous weightless dub.

After setting 2024 on the good foot with a cut for Future Retro London at the head of the year, Refreshers fizz up a pleading ‘80s soul vocal with rambunctious jump up choppage in ‘The Infinite’, making ample room for blissed breakdowns, before dialling up the lushness on ‘The Infinite Dub’, which leaves the breaks for dust and beautifully twirls the hair-kissing pads... more

title_full:
K. Freund

              —
              Trash Can Lamb
            
              (Soda Gong)
label: Soda Gong
description:
Trouble Books' Keith Freund gets up close and personal on 'Trash Can Lamb', playing homespun sax and piano phrases over DIY electronic sputters and hiccuping, downsampled loops.

There's something undeniably satisfying about Freund's music; the Akron-based multi-instrumentalist has been recording and collaborating for almost two decades, and his solo output is casual and intimate. It's like hearing someone rehearsing in their bedroom studio, playing to their own internal rhythm... more

label: do you have peace?
description:
Jabu take a big leap skyward on a gorgeous new album of hazed dreampop and burnished bass inspired by classic Cocteau Twins via A.R. Kane - essential listening for fans of HTRK, Rat Heart Ensemble, YL Hooi.

Launching with a dampened crash and slo-mo thuds, 'Oceanside Spider House' is the ideal re-introduction to the Bristol trio of Amos Childs, Alex Rendall and Jasmine Butt, who built a cult following for their blown-out, hypnagogic dub diffractions on 2017's 'Sleep Heavy' for Blackest... more

label: 10k
description:
Brooklyn’s Anysia Kym recycles junglist shrapnel with inventive, freeform and lo-fi pop and R&B inspirations on her most significant solo volley yet

Dovetailing a new generation of artists reframing jungle tropes to their own ends, Anysia Kym chases her Jadasea-hosted ‘Pressure Sensitive’ (2023) album with this 2nd drop and solo debut for her local label 10K. Whilst jungle’s chopped up breaks and slow/fast meter has never been out of earshot for those who grew up with it and still hold a... more

label: Efficient Space
description:
An absolute gem of minimalist post-punk pop jangle from 1980 Coventry finally finds its audience, who are likely to be fans of Antena, Brenda Ray, Vazz, Young Marble Giants, Fire Engines, Maximum Joy.

The epitome of a what-could-have-been band, Skeet were a trio formed in the shadows of Coventry’s renowned 2 Tone scene by brothers Gary & Nigel Meffen, and completed by singer Kay Booth, whose endearingly shy delivery neatly contrast the lads’ spiky, jangling drive. They would... more
